Just got this from John Gilmore (Autism Action Network)

‚ÄúNYC Mayor-elect Adams speaks with mandate protestors, agrees to talks

  (11/4/21) Yesterday New York City Mayor-elect Eric Adams emerged from his office at Brooklyn Boro Hall to interact with a crowd of 300 people protesting the firing of thousands of city employees for refusing the vaccine and Adams's recent statements in support of Covid shot mandates for students.

      Adams walked out of Boro Hall surrounded by a platoon of police officers into the protest. He was carrying a cup of coffee and made his way through the people to cross the street to the Brooklyn Municipal Building. A few moments later, Adams came back outside and spoke to members of the crowd. He offered to meet with representatives from the protesting groups. I spoke briefly with Adams and he gave what he said was his private phone number to me and another demonstrator.

     Adams then crossed the street back to Boro Hall and just before he entered the building, he invited a small group of protestors to come into his office for a discussion.  Thirty minutes later the group returned from the meeting. Jo Speakstruth, a teacher's aide who was fired for refusing the shot,  was one of the people who spoke with Adams in his office and said that he was offering to formally meet with a contingent of fired workers from the various New York City departments.   A committee of representatives of terminated employees is being organized to meet with Adams.

     During the primaries Adams expressed opposition to mandates for teachers of students. But on October 15, in a radio interview, Adams did a complete about-face saying, "This is a city and country where we do vaccinate. I was vaccinated for smallpox, mumps, measles and so many others," Adams told WCBS Newsradio 880. "We already have a system in place that states before you start school you receive your vaccination. It is to protect the child and the student population. So I say yes if its FDA approved, we should mandate it like we mandate with other vaccinations."

     In a television appearance yesterday, however,  on MSNBC's Morning Joe Adams said,  "We need to revisit how we are going to address the vaccine mandate." So it appears Adams may be open to changing New York City Policy regarding employees, which is a good thing, but he may have a greater commitment to mandatory shots for students.

     If you value the information and advocacy brought to you by the Autism Action Network, please support us in our one fundraising drive of the year by donating here.

     Please share this message with friends and family, and please post to social networks while we still can."
